        If a global section <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}^n f_*\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> is of Hodge degree <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(p,q)]]></fr:tex> at a point, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> is everywhere of degree <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(p,q)]]></fr:tex>.
        In particular, if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n=2]]></fr:tex> and if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> is, at some point <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex>, the cohomology class of a divisor of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X_s]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> is everywhere the cohomology class of a divisor, and, if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is smooth, is even defined by a divisor <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:tree
