type="local"
href="K1971.xml"
addr="K1971"
title="Nilpotent connections and the monodromy theorem. Applications of a result of Turritin">K1971</fr:link>]).
        Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> be a smooth connected scheme, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[s\in  S]]></fr:tex> a point, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  X\to  S]]></fr:tex> a proper smooth morphism, and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> a direct factor of the local system <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}^i f_*\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>, which is pointwise a Hodge sub-structure.
        Then the following conditions are equivalent:

        
 <html:ol
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
          
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
            The Hodge structure of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> is locally constant.
          </html:li>

          
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(b) &quot;">
            The representation <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[P_s]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi _1(S,s)]]></fr:tex> factors through a finite quotient of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi _1(S,s)]]></fr:tex>.
          </html:li>

          
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(c) &quot;">
            There exists a finite non-empty étale covering <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[u\colon  S'\to  S]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[u^*P]]></fr:tex> is a constant family of Hodge structures.
          </html:li>

        </html:ol></fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
